Definition 1.3.10. Let $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ be two Krull-Schmidt categories with respective pairwise compatibility conditions $\mathbf{P}$ and $\mathbf{Q}$. Suppose these compatibility conditions induce the $\mathbf{P}$-cluster theory and $\mathbf{Q}$-cluster theory of $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$, respectively. Suppose there exists a functor $F:\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})\to\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{Q}}(\mathcal{D})$ such that $F$ is an injection on objects and an injection from $\mathbf{P}$-mutations to $\mathbf{Q}$-mutations. Suppose also there is a natural transformation $\eta:I_{\mathbf{P},\mathcal{C}}\to I_{\mathbf{Q},\mathcal{D}}\circ F$ whose morphisms $\eta_{T}:I_{\mathbf{P},\mathcal{C}}(T)\to I_{\mathbf{Q},\mathcal{D}}\circ F(T)$ are all injections. Then we call $(F,\eta):\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})\to\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{Q}}(% \mathcal{D})$ an embedding of cluster theories.
Definition 4.1.2. An arc with endpoints in $\mathcal{E}$ is a pair of endpoints $\theta=(\overline{a},\overline{b})\in\mathcal{E}\times\mathcal{E}$ such that $\overline{a}<\overline{b}$. Let $M_{|a,b|}$ be the indecomposable in ${\mathcal{C}(A_{\mathbb{R}})}$ that is the image of the indecomposable with the same name in $\operatorname{rep}_{k}(A_{\mathbb{R}})$. The arc associated to $M_{|a,b|}$ is the arc whose endpoints are • $(a,-)$ if $a\in|a,b|$ and $(a,+)$ if $a\notin|a,b|$, and • $(b,-)$ if $b\notin|a,b|$ and $(b,+)$ if $b\in|a,b|$. Note that if $M_{|a,b|}=M_{\{a\}}$ then the arc associated to $M_{|a,b|}$ is $((a,-),(a,+))$.
Definition 2.3.9. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a Krull-Schmidt category and $\mathbf{P}$ a pairwise compatibility condition on its indecomposables such that $\mathbf{P}$ induces the $\mathbf{P}$-cluster theory of $\mathcal{C}$. Let $\overline{\mu}_{1},\overline{\mu}_{2}:\mathcal{I}\to\mathcal{S}et$ be two $\mathbf{P}$-mutation paths and suppose $\overline{\mu}_{1}(1,0)=\overline{\mu}_{2}(0,0)$ and $\overline{\mu}_{1}(1,1)=\overline{\mu}_{2}(0,1)$. We define the composition of $\mathbf{P}$-mutation paths, denoted $\overline{\mu}_{1}\cdot\overline{\mu}_{2}$ in the following way: $\displaystyle\overline{\mu}_{1}\cdot\overline{\mu}_{2}(s,i)$ $\displaystyle:=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}\overline{\mu}_{1}(2s,i)&0\leq s\leq% \frac{1}{2}\\ \overline{\mu}_{2}(2s-1,i)&\frac{1}{2}\leq s\leq 1.\end{array}\right.$ $\displaystyle\overline{\mu}_{1}\cdot\overline{\mu}_{2}((s,0)\to(s,1))$ $\displaystyle:=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}\overline{\mu}_{1}((2s,0)\to(2s,1))&0% \leq s\leq\frac{1}{2}\\ \overline{\mu}_{2}((2s-1,0)\to(2s-1,1))&\frac{1}{2}\leq s\leq 1.\end{array}\right.$
Definition 3.3.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a Krull-Schmidt category and $\mathbf{P}$ a pairwise compatibility condition on the indecomposables of $\mathcal{C}$ such that $\mathbf{P}$ induces the $\mathbf{P}$-cluster theory $\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})$ of $\mathcal{C}$. Suppose there exists a subcategory $\mathscr{S}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})\subset\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{% C})$ with the following properties: • For each $\mathbf{P}$-cluster $T$ in $\mathscr{S}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})$ every $X\in T$ is $\mathbf{P}$-mutable and its $\mathbf{P}$-mutation $(T\setminus\{X\})\cup\{Y\}$ is also in $\mathscr{S}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})$. • For each $\mathbf{P}$-cluster $T$ in $\mathscr{S}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})$ the category $\mathcal{C}/\mathop{\text{add}}T$ is abelian. • If $T$ is a $\mathbf{P}$-cluster such that all $X\in T$ are $\mathbf{P}$-mutable and $\mathcal{C}/\mathop{\text{add}}T$ is abelian then $T$ is in $\mathscr{S}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})$. We call such a $\mathscr{S}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})$ the $\mathbf{P}$-cluster structure of $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 2.1.5. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a Krull-Schmidt category and $\mathbf{P}$ a pairwise compatibility condition on its indecomposables such that $\mathbf{P}$ induces the $\mathbf{P}$-cluster theory of $\mathcal{C}$. Let $Z=\{1,\ldots,n\}$ or $Z={\mathbb{Z}}_{>0}$. For each $i\in Z$ let $\mu_{i}$ be a continuous $\mathbf{P}$-mutation such that the target of $\mu_{i}$ is the source of $\mu_{i+1}$ when $i,i+1\in Z$. We call $\{\mu_{i}\}_{i\in Z}$ a sequence of continuous $\mathbf{P}$-mutations. If each $\mu_{i}$ mutates only one element of $T_{i}$ we may also say that $\{\mu_{i}\}$ is a sequence of $\mathbf{P}$-mutations.
Definition 4.2.6. Let $\theta=\{\overline{a},\overline{b}\}$ be an arc with endpoints in $\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}$. Suppose $\overline{a}=(|s_{m},s_{m+1}|,\varepsilon)$ and $\overline{b}=(|s_{n},s_{n+1}|,\varepsilon^{\prime})$. Since we have covered $\overline{a},\overline{b}\in\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}^{\downarrow}$ or $\in\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}^{\uparrow}$ in Definition 4.2.4 we may assume by symmetry that $m$ is odd and $n$ is even. If $\varepsilon=-$ let $s_{a}=s_{m}$ and if $\varepsilon=+$ let $s_{a}=s_{m+1}$. If $\varepsilon^{\prime}=-$ let $s_{b}=s_{n}$ and if $\varepsilon^{\prime}=+$ let $s_{b}=s_{n+1}$. Then • If $s_{a}<s_{b}$ we say $\overline{a}$ is the source and $\overline{b}$ is the target. • If $s_{b}<s_{a}$ we say $\overline{a}$ is the target and $\overline{b}$ is the source. • If $s_{b}=s_{a}$ then $\{\varepsilon,\varepsilon^{\prime}\}=\{{-},{+}\}$. (i) If $\varepsilon=-$ then we say $\overline{a}$ is the source and $\overline{b}$ is the target. (ii) If $\varepsilon^{\prime}=-$ then we say $\overline{b}$ is the source and $\overline{a}$ is the target.
