Definition 2.1.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a Krull-Schmidt category and $\mathbf{P}$ a pairwise compatibility condition on the indecomposables in $\mathcal{C}$ such that $\mathbf{P}$ induces the $\mathbf{P}$-cluster theory of $\mathcal{C}$. For any $\mathbf{P}$-cluster $T$, we call the identity function $\mathop{\text{id}}_{T}:T\to T$ a trivial $\mathbf{P}$-mutation.
Definition 4.2.4. Let $\theta=\{\overline{a},\overline{b}\}$ be an arc with endpoints in $\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}$. The orientation of $\theta$ is a bijection $\{\overline{a},\overline{b}\}\to\{\text{source},\text{target}\}$ which we define the following way. If $\overline{a}<\overline{b}\in\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}^{\downarrow}$ or $\in\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}^{\uparrow}$ then we say $\overline{a}$ is the source and $\overline{b}$ is the target. First suppose both $a$ and $b$ are real numbers (as opposed to one of the $|s_{n},s_{n+1}|$’s). If $a=b$ we have covered this and if $a<b$ in ${\mathbb{R}}$ we say $\overline{a}$ is the source and $\overline{b}$ is the target.
Definition 3.1.3. Let $T_{\mathbf{N}_{\overline{\infty}}}$ be an $\mathbf{N}_{\overline{\infty}}$-cluster in $\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{N}_{\overline{\infty}}}(\mathcal{C}(A_{\overline{\infty}}))$. Define $T_{\mathbf{E}_{\overline{\infty}}}$ to be $T_{\mathbf{E}_{\overline{\infty}}}:=T_{\infty}\cup\left\{M_{\theta}:\theta\in T% _{\mathbf{N}_{\overline{\infty}}}\right\}.$
Definition 4.0.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ be a Krull-Schmidt categories. Let $\mathbf{P}$ and $\mathbf{Q}$ be pairwise compatibility conditions in $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ such that they, respectively, induce the cluster theories $\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})$ and $\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{Q}}(\mathcal{D})$. A weak equivalence of cluster theories is an embedding of cluster theories $(F,\eta):\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})\to\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{Q}}(% \mathcal{D})$ such that $F$ is an isomorphism of categories. We instead say $(F,\eta)$ is an isomorphism of cluster theories if additionally each $\eta_{T}$ is an isomorphism.
Definition 2.3.2. Define a category $\mathcal{I}$ whose objects are pairs $(x,i)\in[0,1]\times\{0,1\}$. Consider $[0,1]$ and $\{0,1\}$ with their respective usual total ordering. Morphisms in $\mathcal{I}$ are defined by $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{I}}\left((s,i),(t,j)\right):=\left\{\begin{array}% []{ll}\{*\}&s<t\text{ or }(s=t\text{ and }i\leq j)\\ \emptyset&\text{otherwise.}\end{array}\right.$ Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a Krull-Schmidt category and $\mathbf{P}$ a pairwise compatibility condition on its indecomposables such that $\mathbf{P}$ induces the $\mathbf{P}$-cluster theory of $\mathcal{C}$. Let $\overline{\mu}:\mathcal{I}\to ets$ be a functor such that $\overline{\mu}*:\overline{\mu}(s,0)\to\overline{\mu}(s,1)$ is a (possibly trivial) $\mathbf{P}$-mutation in $\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})$. Then we call $\overline{\mu}$ a $\mathbf{P}$-mutation path.
Definition 1.3.7. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a skeletally small Krull-Schmidt additive category and $\mathbf{P}$ a pairwise compatibility condition on its (isomorphism classes of) indecomposable objects. Suppose that for each (isomorphism class of) indecomposable $X$ in a maximally $\mathbf{P}$-compatible set $T$ there exists none or one (isomorphism class of) indecomposable $Y$ such that $\{X,Y\}$ is not $\mathbf{P}$-compatible but $(T\setminus\{X\})\cup\{Y\}$ is maximally $\mathbf{P}$-compatible. Then • We call the maximally $\mathbf{P}$-compatible sets $\mathbf{P}$-clusters. • We call a function of the form $\mu:T\to(T\setminus\{X\})\cup\{Y\}$ such that $\mu Z=Z$ when $Z\neq X$ and $\mu X=Y$ a $\mathbf{P}$-mutation or $\mathbf{P}$-mutation at $X$. • If there exists a $\mathbf{P}$-mutation $\mu:T\to(T\setminus\{X\})\cup\{Y\}$ we say $X\in T$ is $\mathbf{P}$-mutable. • The subcategory $\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})$ of $\mathcal{S}\text{et}$ whose objects are $\mathbf{P}$-clusters and whose morphisms are generated by $\mathbf{P}$-mutations (and identity functions) is called the $\mathbf{P}$-cluster theory of $\mathcal{C}$. • The functor $I_{\mathbf{P},\mathcal{C}}:\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})\to\mathcal{S}% \text{et}$ is the inclusion of the subcategory.
Definition 3.3.9. Recall $T_{\pi,i}$ from Definition 3.2.9. For each $i\in{\mathbb{Z}}$ let $S_{\pi,i}=T_{\pi,i}\setminus\{M(\mathfrak{f}^{-1}(-\infty,\,i+1))\}$.
Definition 2.2.3. Let $\mathcal{C}(A_{\overline{\infty}})$ be the $k$-linear additive category whose objects are the 0 object and direct sums of diagonals $\theta$ of $\overline{\mathcal{C}_{\infty}}$ and whose morphisms on diagonals are given by $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}(A_{\overline{\infty}})}(\theta,\theta^{\prime}% )=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}k&(\theta=\theta^{\prime})\text{ or }(\theta\text{% crosses }\theta^{\prime})\\ 0&\text{otherwise.}\end{array}\right.$ Let $f:\theta\to\theta^{\prime}$ and $g:\theta^{\prime}\to\theta^{\prime\prime}$ be morphisms on diagonals in $\mathcal{C}(A_{\overline{\infty}})$. Note $f$ and $g$ are also considered as scalars in $k$. Define composition as $g\circ f=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}g\cdot f\in\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}(% A_{\overline{\infty}})}(\theta,\theta^{\prime\prime})&(\theta=\theta^{\prime}% \text{ or }\theta^{\prime}=\theta^{\prime\prime})\text{ and }((\theta\text{ % crosses }\theta^{\prime\prime})\text{ or }\theta=\theta^{\prime\prime})\\ 0&\text{otherwise}.\end{array}\right.$
Definition 1.3.2. Let $V$ be an indecomposable in ${\mathcal{C}(A_{\mathbb{R}})}$. The g-vector of $V$ is the element $[P_{V}]-[Q_{V}]$ in ${K_{0}^{\text{split}}({\mathcal{C}(A_{\mathbb{R}})})}$ where $Q_{V}\to P_{V}\to V\to 0$ is the minimal projective resolution of $V$ in $\operatorname{rep}_{k}(A_{\mathbb{R}})$.
Definition 1.1.3. Let $A_{\mathbb{R}}$ be a continuous quiver of type $A$ and $I\subset{\mathbb{R}}$ be an interval. We denote by $M_{I}$ the representation of $A_{\mathbb{R}}$ where $\displaystyle M_{I}(x)$ $\displaystyle=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}k&x\in I\\ 0&\text{otherwise}\end{array}\right.$ $\displaystyle M_{I}(x,y)$ $\displaystyle=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}1_{k}&y\preceq x\in I\\ 0&\text{otherwise.}\end{array}\right.$ We call $M_{I}$ an interval indecomposable.
Definition 4.1.7. We now define the $k$-linear Krull-Schmidt category $\mathcal{C}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}$ similarly to $\mathcal{C}(A_{\overline{\infty}})$ in Definition 2.2.3. The objects of $\mathcal{C}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}$ are the 0 object and direct suns of arcs with endpoints in $\mathcal{E}$. For a pair of arcs $\theta$ and $\theta^{\prime}$ we define hom sets as $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}}(\theta,\theta^{\prime})=% \left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}k&(\theta\text{ and }\theta^{\prime}\text{ cross})% \text{ or }(\theta=\theta^{\prime})\\ 0&\text{otherwise}.\end{array}\right.$ Let $f:\theta\to\theta^{\prime}$ and $g:\theta^{\prime}\to\theta^{\prime\prime}$ be morphisms (also scalars in $k$). We define composition as $g\circ f=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}g\cdot f\in\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}_% {A_{\mathbb{R}}}}(\theta,\theta^{\prime\prime})&(\theta=\theta^{\prime}\text{ % or }\theta^{\prime}=\theta^{\prime\prime})\text{ and }((\theta\text{ crosses }% \theta^{\prime\prime})\text{ or }\theta=\theta^{\prime\prime})\\ 0&\text{otherwise}.\end{array}\right.$ We say $\{\theta,\theta^{\prime}\}$ is $\mathbf{N}_{\overline{{\mathbb{R}}}}$-compatible if and only if $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}}(\theta,\theta^{\prime})=0$ or $\theta=\theta^{\prime}$.
