Definition 1.1.7. Let $A_{\mathbb{R}}$ be a continuous quiver of type $A$. By $\operatorname{rep}_{k}(A_{\mathbb{R}})$ we denote the full subcategory of pointwise finite-dimensional representations whose objects are finitely generated by the indecomposable projectives in Theorem 1.1.6. By [15, Theorem 3.0.1] this category is Krull-Schmidt with global dimension 1.
Definition 1.3.4. • Let $V$ and $W$ be two indecomposables in ${\mathcal{C}(A_{\mathbb{R}})}$ with g-vectors $[P_{V}]-[Q_{V}]$ and $[P_{W}]-[Q_{W}]$. We say $\{V,W\}$ is $\mathbf{E}$-compatible if $\langle[P_{V}]-[Q_{V}]\,,\,[P_{W}]-[Q_{W}]\rangle\geq 0\qquad\text{and}\qquad% \langle[P_{W}]-[Q_{W}]\,,\,[P_{V}]-[Q_{V}]\rangle\geq 0.$ • A set $T$ is called $\mathbf{E}$-compatible if for every $V,W\in T$ the set $\{V,W\}$ is $\mathbf{E}$-compatible. If $T$ is maximally $\mathbf{E}$-compatible then we call $T$ an $\mathbf{E}$-cluster. • Let $T$ be an $\mathbf{E}$-cluster and $V\in T$ such that there exists $W\notin T$ where $\{V,W\}$ is not $\mathbf{E}$-compatible but $(T\setminus\{V\})\cup\{W\}$ is $\mathbf{E}$-compatible. Then we say $V$ is $\mathbf{E}$-mutable. The bijection (see Theorem 1.3.5) $T\to(T\setminus\{V\})\cup\{W\})$ given by $V\mapsto W$ and $X\mapsto X$ if $X\neq V$ is called an $\mathbf{E}$-mutation or $\mathbf{E}$-mutation at $V$.
Definition 2.3.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a Krull-Schmidt category and $\mathbf{P}$ a pairwise compatibility condition on its indecomposables such that $\mathbf{P}$ induces the $\mathbf{P}$-cluster theory of $\mathcal{C}$. Let $\overline{\mu}=\{{{}_{i}\mu}:{{}_{i}T}_{0}\to{{}_{i}}T_{1}\}_{i\in{\mathbb{Z}}}$ be a collection of continuous mutations such that ${{}_{i}T}_{1}={{}_{i+1}T}_{0}$. This yields a diagram in $\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})$: $\xymatrix@C=8ex{\cdots\ar[r]^{-}{{}_{i-1}\mu}&{{}_{i-1}T}_{1}={{}_{i}T}_{0}\ar% [r]^{-}{{}_{i}\mu}&{{}_{i}T}_{1}={{}_{i+1}T}_{0}\ar[r]^{-}{{}_{i+1}\mu}&{{}_{i% +1}T}_{1}={{}_{i+2}T}_{0}\ar[r]^{-}{{}_{i+2}\mu}&\cdots}$ If this diagram has a limit and colimit we call $\overline{\mu}$ a long sequence of continuous mutations and we call the limit and colimit the source and target of $\overline{\mu}$, respectively.
