Definition 4.2.2. Let $A_{\mathbb{R}}$ be a continuous quiver of type $A$ and $\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}$ as we have defined. An arc with endpoints in $\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}$ is an unordered pair $\{\overline{a},\overline{b}\}\subset\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}$ where $\overline{a}\neq\overline{b}$.
Definition 1.3.15. Let $\mathcal{C}A$, $\mathcal{C}B$, and $\mathcal{C}C$ be the sets $\displaystyle\mathcal{C}A$ $\displaystyle=\{(x,y)\in{\mathbb{R}}^{2}:|x-y|<\pi,x\geq 0,y<\pi\}$ $\displaystyle\mathcal{C}B$ $\displaystyle=\left\{(\alpha,\beta)\in{\mathbb{R}}^{2}:-\frac{\pi}{2}<\beta<% \frac{\pi}{2}\text{ and }\beta\leq\alpha<\pi-\beta\right\}$ $\displaystyle\mathcal{C}C$ $\displaystyle=\{(a,b)\in({\mathbb{R}}\cup\{-\infty\})\times{\mathbb{R}}:-% \infty\leq a<b<+\infty\}.$ Define $\mathfrak{g}:\mathcal{C}A\to\mathcal{C}B$ and $\mathfrak{h}:\mathcal{C}B\to\mathcal{C}C$ by $\displaystyle\mathfrak{g}(x,y):$ $\displaystyle=\left(\frac{y+x}{2},\frac{y-x}{2}\right)$ $\displaystyle\mathfrak{h}(\alpha,\beta):$ $\displaystyle=\left(\tan\left(\frac{\alpha-\beta-\pi}{2}\right),\tan\left(% \frac{\alpha+\beta}{2}\right)\right)$ We define $\mathfrak{f}:\mathcal{C}A\to\mathcal{C}C$ by $\mathfrak{f}(x,y)=\mathfrak{h}\circ\mathfrak{g}(x,y)$. In [16, Proposition 5.4.3] the authors show $\mathfrak{f}$ is a bijection.
