compatible}\}$ $\displaystyle\mathcal{P}(T)$ $\displaystyle:=T\cup\{\pi_{i}:T\cup\{\pi_{i}\}\text{ is }\mathbf{N}_{\infty}% \text{-compatible}\}.$ We call $\mathcal{P}(\mathcal{A}(T))$ the adic completion of $T$ and $\mathcal{A}(\mathcal{P}(T))$ the Prüfer completion of $T$.
Definition 1.3.11. Let $\{a_{i}\}_{i\in{\mathbb{Z}}}$ be a collection of real numbers such that • $a_{i}<a_{i+1}$ for all $i\in{\mathbb{Z}}$ and • $\lim_{i\to-\infty}a_{i},\lim_{i\to+\infty}a_{i}\in{\mathbb{Z}}$. Let $a_{-\infty}=\lim_{i\to-\infty}a_{i}$ and $a_{+\infty}=\lim_{i\to+\infty}a_{i}$. For each $i,j,\ell\in{\mathbb{Z}}$ such that $l\geq 0$ and $0\leq j\leq 2^{\ell}$ define $a_{i,j,\ell}:=a_{i}+\left(\frac{j}{2^{\ell}}\right)(a_{i+1}-a_{i}).$ For each $a_{i}$, we define the following $\mathbf{E}$-compatible set: $\displaystyle T_{a_{i}}:=$ $\displaystyle\left\{M_{(a_{i,j,\ell},\,a_{i,j+1,\ell})}:j,\ell\in{\mathbb{Z}},% \,\ell\geq 0,\,0\leq j<2^{\ell}\right\}$ $\displaystyle\cup\left\{M_{\{x\}}:x\in(a_{i},a_{i}+1),\,x\neq a_{i,j,l},\,\,j,% \ell\in{\mathbb{Z}},\,\ell\geq 0,\,0\leq j<2^{\ell}\right\},$ Note that for any $a_{i}$ and $a_{j}$ then $T_{a_{i}}\cup T_{a_{j}}$ is $\mathbf{E}$-compatible. Now, for each $i\in{\mathbb{Z}}$ such that $i<a_{-\infty}$ or $i\geq a_{+\infty}$ define a similar type of $\mathbf{E}$-compatible set: $\displaystyle T_{i}:=$ $\displaystyle\left\{M_{(i+j/2^{\ell},i+(j+1)/2^{\ell})}:j,\ell\in{\mathbb{Z}},% \,\ell\geq 0,\,0\leq j<2^{\ell}\right\}\cup\{P_{i+1}\}$ $\displaystyle\cup\left\{M_{\{x\}}:x\in(i,i+1),\,x\neq i+j/2^{\ell},\,j,\ell\in% {\mathbb{Z}},\,\ell\geq 0,\,0\leq j<2^{\ell}\right\}$ The $\mathbf{E}$-compatible set we want is $\displaystyle T_{\infty}:=$ $\displaystyle\left(\bigcup_{i\in{\mathbb{Z}}}T_{a_{i}}\right)\cup\left(\bigcup% _{i<a_{-\infty}\text{ or }i\geq a_{+\infty}}T_{i}\right)$ $\displaystyle\cup\{M_{(a_{-\infty},a_{+\infty})},P_{+\infty}\}\cup\left\{P_{i}% :i\leq a_{-\infty}\text{ or }i\geq a_{+\infty}\right\}.$
Definition 4.1.4. Let $\Phi:\text{Ind}({\mathcal{C}(A_{\mathbb{R}})})\to\{\text{arcs with endpoints % in }\mathcal{E}\}$ be given by sending $M_{|a,b|}$ to the arc associated to $M_{|a,b|}$. It follows from Definition 4.1.2 that $\Phi$ is well-defined.
Definition 2.4.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a Krull-Schmidt category and $\mathbf{P}$ a pairwise compatibility condition on its indecomposables such that $\mathbf{P}$ induces the $\mathbf{P}$-cluster theory of $\mathcal{C}$. Suppose the morphisms of $\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})$, denoted $(\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C}))_{1}$, form a set. Then any $\mathbf{P}$-mutation path $\overline{\mu}$ induces a function $p_{\overline{\mu}}:[0,1]\to(\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C}))_{1}$.
Definition 3.3.5. Let $(F,\eta):\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})\to\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{Q}}(% \mathcal{D})$ be an embedding of cluster theories. We say $(F,\eta)$ restricts to an embedding of cluster structures if the following hold. • The pairwise compatibility conditions $\mathbf{P}$ and $\mathbf{Q}$ induce the cluster structures $\mathscr{S}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})$ and $\mathscr{S}_{\mathbf{Q}}(\mathcal{D})$, respectively. • If $T$ is a $\mathbf{P}$-cluster in $\mathscr{S}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})$ then $F(T)$ is in $\mathscr{S}_{\mathbf{Q}}(\mathcal{D})$.
