Definition 2.1.2. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a Krull-Schmidt category and $\mathbf{P}$ a pairwise compatibility condition on the indecomposables in $\mathcal{C}$ such that $\mathbf{P}$ induces the $\mathbf{P}$-cluster theory of $\mathcal{C}$. Let $T$ and $T^{\prime}$ be $\mathbf{P}$-clusters. Let $S\subset T$ such that there exists a bijection $\mu:T\to T^{\prime}$ where $\mu X=X$ if and only if $X\notin S$. Let $S^{\prime}=\mu(S)$ and further assume that for all $\mu X\in S^{\prime}$ (i) $\mu X\notin T$ and (ii) $\{X,\mu X\}$ is not $\mathbf{P}$-compatible. Finally, suppose there exist injections $f_{\mu}:S\to[0,1]$ and $g_{\mu}:S^{\prime}\to[0,1]$ such that • The following equality holds: $g_{\mu}\circ\mu|_{S}=f_{\mu}$, $\xymatrix@C=3ex{S\ar[rr]^{-}{\mu|_{S}}\ar[dr]_{-}{f_{\mu}}&&S^{\prime}\ar[dl]^% {-}{g_{\mu}}\\ &[0,1].&}$ • For any subinterval $J\subset[0,1]$ where $0\in J$ and $1\notin J$ the following is a $\mathbf{P}$-cluster: $(T\setminus f_{\mu}^{-1}(J))\cup g_{\mu}^{-1}(J)=(T^{\prime}\setminus g_{\mu}^% {-1}(\bar{J}))\cup f_{\mu}(\bar{J}),$ where $\bar{J}=[0,1]\setminus J$. If all this holds we call $\mu$ a continuous $\mathbf{P}$-mutation.
Definition 4.2.5. Let $\theta=\{\overline{a},\overline{b}\}$ be an arc with endpoints in $\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}$. Now suppose one endpoint of $\theta$ is of the form $(|s_{n},s_{n+1}|,\varepsilon)$ and the other is $(x,\varepsilon^{\prime})$ for $x\in{\mathbb{R}}$. Since our pairs are unordered assume that $\overline{a}=(|s_{n},s_{n+1}|,\varepsilon)$ and $\overline{b}=(x,\varepsilon^{\prime})$. Note $x\neq s_{m}$ for any sink or source (including $\pm\infty$) in $A_{\mathbb{R}}$. • If $x<s_{n}$ then set $\overline{b}$ as the source and $\overline{a}$ as the target. • If $x>s_{n+1}$ then set $\overline{a}$ as the source and $\overline{b}$ as the target. • If $s_{n}<x<s_{n+1}$ then we check $\varepsilon$ in $(|s_{n},s_{n+1}|,\varepsilon)$. (i) If $\varepsilon=-$ then we set $\overline{a}$ as the source and $\overline{b}$ as the target. (ii) If $\varepsilon=+$ then we set $\overline{b}$ as the source and $\overline{a}$ as the target.
